\begin_layout Proof
First, consider a measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Omega,\mathcal{B}\left(\Omega\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 such that any finite dimensional projection of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:finite-projection-markov"

\end_inset

.
 We will show this measure is a Markov measure with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}_{t}$
\end_inset

 and transition kernels as given.
 It is immediate that this measure has the desired restriction 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}_{t}$
\end_inset

, and thus it only remains to be shown that the transition kernels associated
 with this measure are as desired, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 is a Markov measure.
 First we show the transition kernels are as desired.
 Pick any 
\begin_inset Formula $u>t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\in\mathcal{F}_{u}$
\end_inset

, and note 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mathbb{P}_{t,u}\left(dx\times B\right) & = & \int_{A}p\left(B,u\mid x,t\right)\mathbb{P}_{t}\left(dx\right)\\
 & = & \mathbb{E}\left[p\left(B,u\mid X_{t},t\right)\mid\mathbf{1}_{X_{t}=x}\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

which gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}_{u}\left(B\mid X_{t}=x\right)=p\left(B,u\mid x,t\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}-a.e.$
\end_inset

 as desired.
 We finally show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:memorylessness"

\end_inset

 i.e.
 is memoryless, which is sufficient to show it is a Markov measure.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $t\leq u<v$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{B}\left(\mathbb{R}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, let 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq s_{1}\leq\cdots\leq s_{n}=u$
\end_inset

 and pick 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}\dots,A_{n}\in\mathcal{B}\left(\mathbb{R}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
 &  & \mathbb{P}_{s_{1},\dots,s_{n},v}\left(A_{1}\times\cdots\times A_{n}\times A\right)\\
 & = & \int_{A_{1}\times\cdots\times A_{n}}p\left(A,v\mid y_{n},u\right)\mathbb{P}_{s_{1},\dots,s_{n}}\left(dy_{1,\dots,n}\right)\\
 & = & \mathbb{E}\left[\mathbf{1}_{X_{s_{1}}\in A_{1}}\cdots\mathbf{1}_{X_{s_{n}}\in A_{n}}p\left(A,v\mid X_{u},u\right)\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $dy_{1,\dots,n}=dy_{1}\times\cdots\times dy_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 In a similar argument as above, this gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}\left(X_{v}\in A\mid\mathcal{F}_{:u}\right)=p\left(A,v\mid X_{u},u\right)=\mathbb{P}\left(X_{v}\in A\mid\mathcal{F}_{u}\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}-a.e.$
\end_inset

 as desired.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Now, we show the converse.
 Consider a Markov measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Omega,\mathcal{B}\left(\Omega\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}_{t}$
\end_inset

 and the associated transition kernels are as given.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbb{Q}_{t_{1},\dots,t_{n}}:t_{1},\dots,t_{n}\in I\right\} $
\end_inset

 be the set of finite-dimensional projections of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

.
 We will show that this set is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbb{P}_{t_{1},\dots,t_{n}}:t_{1},\dots,t_{n}\in I\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Clearly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}_{t}=\mathbb{P}_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 To complete the proof, we proceed by induction.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}>t$
\end_inset

, and note for 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}\in\mathcal{B}\left(\mathbb{R}\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mathbb{Q}_{t_{1}}\left(A_{1}\right) & = & \mathbb{P}\left(X_{t_{1}}\in A_{1}\right)\\
 & = & \mathbb{E}\left[p\left(A_{1},t_{1}\mid X_{t},t\right)\right]\\
 & = & \int p\left(A_{1},t_{1}\mid y,t\right)\mathbb{Q}_{t}\left(dy\right)\\
 & = & \int p\left(A_{1},t_{1}\mid y,t\right)\mathbb{P}_{t}\left(dy\right)\\
 & = & \mathbb{P}_{t_{1}}\left(A_{1}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Now, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}_{t_{1},\dots,t_{n}}=\mathbb{P}_{t_{1},\dots,t_{n}}$
\end_inset

, and consider 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1},\dots,A_{n+1}\in\mathcal{B}\left(\mathbb{R}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
 &  & \mathbb{Q}_{t_{1},\dots,t_{n+1}}\left(A_{1}\times\cdots\times A_{n+1}\right)\\
 & = & \mathbb{E}\left[\mathbf{1}_{X_{1}\in A_{1}}\cdots\mathbf{1}_{X_{n}\in A_{n}}p\left(A_{n+1},t_{n+1}\mid X_{n},t_{n}\right)\right]\\
 & = & \int\mathbf{1}_{X_{1}\in A_{1}}\cdots\mathbf{1}_{X_{n}\in A_{n}}p\left(A_{n+1},t_{n+1}\mid y_{n},t_{n}\right)\mathbb{Q}_{t_{1},\dots,t_{n}}\left(dy_{1,\dots,n}\right)\\
 & = & \int\mathbf{1}_{X_{1}\in A_{1}}\cdots\mathbf{1}_{X_{n}\in A_{n}}p\left(A_{n+1},t_{n+1}\mid y_{n},t_{n}\right)\mathbb{P}_{t_{1},\dots,t_{n}}\left(dy_{1,\dots,n}\right)\\
 & = & \int_{A_{1}\times\cdots\times A_{n+1}}p\left(dy_{n+1},t_{n+1}\mid y_{n},t_{n}\right)\mathbb{P}_{t_{1},\dots,t_{n}}\left(dy_{1,\dots,n}\right)\\
 & = & \mathbb{P}_{t_{1},\dots,t_{n+1}}\left(A_{1}\times\cdots\times A_{n+1}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and we see the set of finite-dimensional projections of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 at times 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1},\dots,t_{n}\geq t$
\end_inset

 is precisely equal to those given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:finite-projection-markov"

\end_inset

.
 Arguments for times 
\begin_inset Formula $:t$
\end_inset

 and general times 
\begin_inset Formula $t'\in I$
\end_inset

 follow readily, and we conclude that there exists a unique Markov measure
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}_{t}$
\end_inset

 and associated transition kernels as given.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The final major result before we may begin an exploration of the theory
 of Markov bridges proper is one that gives a necessary and sufficient condition
 for a general path measure dominated by a Markov measure to be itself Markov.
 This result will allow us to derive the density of a Markov bridge, whose
 measure is dominated by a Markov measure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be a reference Markov measure and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}\ll\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be a path measure dominated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 is Markov if and only if the Radon-Nikodym derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 can be written 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\mathbb{P}}{d\mathbb{R}}=\alpha_{t}\beta_{t},\mbox{ }\mathbb{R}-a.e.
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{t}$
\end_inset

 are non-negative 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{:t}-$
\end_inset

measurable and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{t:}-$
\end_inset

measurable functions respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Markov Bridge Measures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With a basic understanding of Markov measures, we move now to the topic
 of this thesis.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 can be decomposed as a mixture of measures pinned at times 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1$
\end_inset

 in the following way:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbb{P}=\int_{\mathcal{F}_{0}\otimes\mathcal{F}_{1}}\mathbb{P}\left(\cdot\mid X_{0}=x,X_{1}=y\right)\mathbb{P}_{0,1}\left(dx\times dy\right)\label{eq:bridge-decomposition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Under some general conditions, the measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}\left(\cdot\mid X_{0}=x,X_{1}=y\right)$
\end_inset

 exists for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,y\right)\in\Omega_{0}\times\Omega_{1}$
\end_inset

 and is defined everywhere.
 We will call this measure the bridge measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{x,y}$
\end_inset

 of the Markov measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Bridge measures of Markov measures are Markov
\end_layout

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 be a Markov measure.
 Then, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,y\right)\in\Omega_{0}\times\Omega_{1}$
\end_inset

, the bridge measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{x,y}$
\end_inset

 is also Markov.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in I$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{F}_{:t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\in\mathcal{F}_{t:}$
\end_inset

 be two events.
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula 
